{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "CAISO Business Practice Manual Market Operations regulation service participation requirements regulation up down mileage capacity award telemetry AGC",
    "num_results": 8,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": "report",
      "year_start": 2022,
      "year_end": 2026,
      "range_type": "between"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "46e472c8-5563-451b-b55f-c1b2ca0c2dfe",
        "score": 0.5760503,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2022 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring, California ISO, dated July 2023. It includes Figure 4.4, which illustrates the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2022, comparing regulation up and down for 2021 and 2022. The graph shows that regulation requirements fluctuate throughout the day, with peaks and troughs in demand.\n\nThe text discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2020 to 2022. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with minimum procurement requirements set within the CAISO system. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy. Most requirements are met by California ISO resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_159.jpg",
          "page_num": 159,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "04e62609-f442-4ad1-8d46-a63d66072876",
        "score": 0.56253684,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2023 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2024. It includes Figure 4.4, which illustrates the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2022 and 2023. The graph shows trends for both regulation up and regulation down, with 2023 requirements generally higher than those in 2022, especially during peak hours.\n\nThe text discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2021 to 2023. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with limitations set by minimum procurement requirements within the CAISO system. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy, and most requirements continue to be met by California ISO resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_209.jpg",
          "page_num": 209,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7db8ebd3-aa51-4b3c-9977-19a7f394fdfe",
        "score": 0.5588058,
        "text": "The document discusses the resource adequacy program for the California ISO system, aimed at ensuring sufficient capacity for reliable grid operation. It involves collaboration with the California Energy Commission (CEC), California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC), and other local regulatory authorities to set procurement obligations for load-serving entities.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Purpose**: To ensure the grid has enough capacity to operate reliably, compensating fixed costs of existing generators through bilateral transactions.\n\n2. **Program Components**: \n   - System resource capacity for peak demand.\n   - Local resource capacity for specific areas with limited import capability.\n   - Flexible resource capacity for ramping periods.\n\n3. **Regulatory Requirements**: \n   - Load-serving entities must demonstrate procurement of adequate capacity.\n   - CPUC-jurisdictional entities must show 90% compliance for summer months and 100% for monthly obligations.\n   - The planning reserve margin (PRM) was set between 20-22.5% for 2022-2023.\n\nThe document also highlights the role of regulatory bodies in setting and enforcing these requirements to maintain grid reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_226.jpg",
          "page_num": 226,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ee318a70-0f9f-40a7-b065-113a5a30efce",
        "score": 0.55089784,
        "text": "The document is from the Department of Market Monitoring for the California ISO, dated July 2023. It discusses the limitations on congestion revenue right payments, suggesting they should not exceed the congestion rents collected from transmission constraints. The current auction system is deemed unnecessary by the DMM, which proposes its elimination or a change to a market-based system for congestion revenue rights or locational price swaps.\n\nThe section on \"Congestion revenue right auction returns\" evaluates the auction's performance by comparing revenues from auctioning transmission rights to day-ahead congestion payments. It highlights:\n\n- Auction revenues received by ratepayers (blue bars).\n- Net payments made to non-load-serving entities purchasing rights (green bars).\n- Total ratepayer losses, calculated as the difference between auction revenues and payments to non-load-serving entities (yellow line).\n\nThe document includes references to related proposals and whitepapers for further context.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_198.jpg",
          "page_num": 198,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "782a93a3-5f8e-4506-8e4e-0ba1eb7508b3",
        "score": 0.5502809,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2023 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2024. It highlights key findings and details about the Resource Adequacy Availability Incentive Mechanism (RAAIM) and the Capacity Procurement Mechanism (CPM).\n\n**Key Findings:**\n- In 2023, RAAIM penalties and payments were evenly distributed between generic and flexible resource adequacy resources, totaling about $41 million, with incentive payments around $31 million. This is an increase from 2022.\n- Most RAAIM charges occurred in the third quarter of 2023, averaging $4.4 million per month. The first quarter had the lowest charges, while the second and fourth quarters had higher averages.\n\n**Capacity Procurement Mechanism (CPM):**\n- The CPM provides backstop procurement to ensure sufficient capacity for reliable grid operations, using pay-as-bid competitive solicitations.\n- Scheduling coordinators can submit bids for yearly, monthly, and intra-monthly offers, with a soft offer cap of $6.31/kW-month.\n- The California ISO can procure backstop capacity through competitive solicitations if there is insufficient capacity in annual or monthly resource adequacy plans.\n- The process includes resolving deficiencies in local areas and addressing capacity shortfalls due to planned outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_299.jpg",
          "page_num": 299,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e6672f2b-5068-49b4-be92-c7f9bc93df6f",
        "score": 0.5481248,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated July 2024. It discusses the availability assessment hours for system and local resource adequacy resources, which vary throughout the year. Resources are charged or paid based on their average capacity availability during these hours. If availability is below 94.5%, a non-availability charge is applied, while availability above 98.5% earns an incentive payment. The RAAIM price is set at 60% of the capacity procurement mechanism cost, approximately $3.79/kW-month.\n\nFigure 8.5 illustrates monthly RAAIM penalties and payments to resource adequacy resources from January 2021 to December 2023. The graph shows financial sums related to the California ISO, with penalties in the positive direction and payments in the negative. The chart differentiates between generic and flex penalties and payments. The footnote explains that payments or charges are calculated based on the resource's monthly average capacity and availability standards.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_298.jpg",
          "page_num": 298,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9ce89f8c-6bbf-45ab-8363-d5ef2d99ebb0",
        "score": 0.54614896,
        "text": "The document is a page from the \"2023 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2024. It includes Figure 4.3, which illustrates the quarterly average day-ahead ancillary service requirements from 2021 to 2023. The services are categorized into regulation down, regulation up, spin, and non-spin.\n\nThe text explains that the California ISO calculates regulation requirements based on observed needs from the same period in the previous year and month. These requirements are determined hourly on a monthly basis, with adjustments possible for higher net load variability.\n\nIn 2023, there was a significant increase in day-ahead requirements for regulation down, especially during morning ramps, averaging 901 MW\u2014a 10% increase from 2022. Regulation up requirements remained stable at 407 MW. Figure 4.4 (not shown) is mentioned to summarize the average hourly profile for 2022 and 2023, noting peaks during ramping hours.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_208.jpg",
          "page_num": 208,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "091ba157-5a8c-4cfd-8010-12e50e34355d",
        "score": 0.5460812,
        "text": "The document discusses recommendations and updates from the Department of Market Monitoring (DMM) for the California ISO regarding resource adequacy and market participation. Key points include:\n\n1. **Resource Adequacy Imports**: DMM suggests allowing resource adequacy imports to bid at marginal costs similar to typical gas resources, especially during peak load hours. Over time, a more specific framework for resource adequacy imports is recommended to ensure reliability during supply shortages.\n\n2. **Slice-of-Day Resource Adequacy Framework**: In April 2023, the CPUC adopted a new framework for resource adequacy, focusing on a 24-hour \"slice of day\" approach. This framework will be implemented starting in 2025 and aims to ensure capacity sufficiency throughout the day. It also supports using excess capacity from other resources to charge battery storage.\n\n3. **Capacity Counting for Renewables**: DMM supports changing the capacity counting method for wind and solar from effective load carrying capacity (ELCC) to exceedance values, though it warns against over-reliance on variable energy resources.\n\n4. **Resource Adequacy Performance Incentives**: The ISO uses the Resource Adequacy Availability Incentive Mechanism (RAAIM) to incentivize availability. This mechanism can lead to financial penalties for resource unavailability. As capacity becomes scarcer, the difference between capacity payments and potential penalties increases, which may lead suppliers to sell less reliable capacity. The RAAIM penalty is not performance-based, allowing suppliers to avoid penalties by offering capacity that may not be available when needed.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_44.jpg",
          "page_num": 44,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

