        "score": 0.2643562,
        "text": "The document is a report from the Department of Market Monitoring for the California ISO, focusing on demand response issues and performance in 2024. Key findings include:\n\n1. **Resource Adequacy**: About 85% of resource adequacy requirements were met by demand response capacity during peak load hours, similar to the previous year but improved from earlier years. This improvement is attributed to changes in planning reserve margins and transmission adders.\n\n2. **Performance on High Demand Days**: Approximately 70% of total demand response capacity was dispatched as scheduled on high demand days in the summer. Utility demand response reported 81% of scheduled load reductions, while non-utility third-party providers averaged 54%.\n\n3. **Reliability Demand Response Resources (RDRR)**: Utilities reported high performance for RDRR, with 83% of scheduled load reductions achieved.\n\n4. **Proxy Demand Response**: Bids for proxy demand response were low, with only 44% of capacity bid into the market. However, when dispatched, these resources performed well, achieving 91% of scheduled reductions.\n\n5. **Non-Utility Third-Party Providers**: These providers had high bid availability but low performance, achieving only 54% of scheduled reductions.\n\n6. **Regulatory Clarification**: In July 2023, the California Public Utilities Commission clarified that the ISO should dispatch reliability demand response during an Emergency Alert (EEA) Watch. However, this was not done during an EEA Watch in July 2024.\n\nThe report highlights the need for improvements in demand response performance, especially from non-utility providers, and the importance of regulatory compliance in dispatching resources during emergencies.",
