        "text": "The document provides an analysis of demand response market participation in the California ISO market during 20 high load days in summer 2024. Demand response accounted for about 2.6% of total system resource adequacy capacity from July to September 2024, averaging 1,414 MW. This is a decline from previous summers' 3-4% due to changes by the CPUC.\n\nThe demand response capacity is divided into three types:\n\n1. **Utility Demand Response Programs**: Managed by utilities, these programs account for about 76% of demand response used to meet resource adequacy requirements.\n\n2. **Supply Plan (Third Party) Demand Response**: Developed by non-utility providers, this accounts for about 18% of demand response capacity.\n\n3. **Non-CPUC Jurisdictional Load Serving Entities**: Such as municipal utilities, these entities use about 75 MW or 6% of demand response capacity.\n\nThe document also notes that the ISO issued an Energy Emergency Alert and Restricted Maintenance Operation notices during the high load days.",
